a. Inconcinnity. Suetonius takes no pains to produce con- cinnity by means of ligures of speech and rhetorical devices. Figures of rhetoric, comparatively speaking, seldom occur and are sometimes not employed of set purpose. Inconcinnity is affected in various ways, even in the expression of correlative members:

pratnitam ct sine framenta stipendioque operam, dni. 68.1 ; siae di vinitas siae aliana coniectura, Jni. 1. 3 ; taciti et ibidem statim, Aug. 39; in continentem lenioribusque panio condicionibus, Aac. 65. 3; ad decli nondam invidiam et t . . . operanaarearnl. 4.1; in memoriam . . . oei qnod . . . prospere generamina. 7.1; imposne mentis an simulata dementia incertam, Ana. 19. 2.
